& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Chest CT angiography (CTA) is essential in the diagnosis of acute aortic syndromes. Chest CTA quality can be optimized with attention to technical parameters pertaining to noncontrast imaging, timing of contrast-enhanced imaging, contrast material volume, kilovolt potential, tube-current modulation, and decisions regarding electrocardiographic-gating and ultra-fast imaging, which may affect the accurate diagnosis of acute aortic syndromes. An understanding of methods to apply to address suboptimal image quality is useful, as the accurate identification of acute aortic syndromes is essential for appropriate patient management. Acute aortic syndromes have high morbidity and mortality, particularly when involving the ascending aorta, and include classic aortic dissection, penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer, and acute intramural hematoma. An understanding of the pathogenesis and distinguishing imaging features of acute aortic syndromes and aortic rupture and some less common manifestations is helpful when interpreting imaging examinations. Related entities, such as ulcerated plaque, ulcerlike projections, and intramural blood pools, and mimics, such as vasculitis and aortic thrombus, are important to recognize; knowledge of these is important to avoid interpretive pitfalls. In addition, an awareness of postsurgical aortic changes can be useful when interpreting CTA examinations when patient history is incomplete. The authors review technical considerations when performing CTA, discuss acute aortic syndromes, and highlight diagnostic challenges encountered when interpreting aortic CTA examinations.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2021</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021200055">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021200055">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic" aria-label="Value of precontrast imaging. (a) Axial CTA image shows an endovascular stent with high-attenuation opacification in the lumen. Note the perigraft space with mild high-attenuation contents (arrow), raising the question of endoleak. (b) Axial precontrast CTA image shows high attenuation (arrow) in the perigraft space, indicating acute hematoma rather than endoleak."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig1a.jpeg" height="1642" width="1338" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Value of precontrast imaging. <b>(a)</b> Axial CTA image shows an endovascular stent with high-attenuation opacification in the lumen. Note the perigraft space with mild high-attenuation contents (arrow), raising the question of endoleak. <b>(b)</b> Axial precontrast CTA image shows high attenuation (arrow) in the perigraft space, indicating acute hematoma rather than endoleak.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic" aria-label="Value of precontrast imaging. (a) Axial CTA image shows an endovascular stent with high-attenuation opacification in the lumen. Note the perigraft space with mild high-attenuation contents (arrow), raising the question of endoleak. (b) Axial precontrast CTA image shows high attenuation (arrow) in the perigraft space, indicating acute hematoma rather than endoleak."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig1b.jpeg" height="1642" width="1312" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Value of precontrast imaging. <b>(a)</b> Axial CTA image shows an endovascular stent with high-attenuation opacification in the lumen. Note the perigraft space with mild high-attenuation contents (arrow), raising the question of endoleak. <b>(b)</b> Axial precontrast CTA image shows high attenuation (arrow) in the perigraft space, indicating acute hematoma rather than endoleak.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic" aria-label="Pulsation artifact and high-pitch imaging. (a) Axial CTA image shows pulsation artifact (black arrows) in the ascending aorta, with a focal contour abnormality suspicious for aneurysm (white arrow). (b) Axial high-pitch nongated CTA image obtained to clarify the pulsation artifact shows this as a high aberrant origin of the right coronary artery (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig2a.jpeg" height="1275" width="1341" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Pulsation artifact and high-pitch imaging. <b>(a)</b> Axial CTA image shows pulsation artifact (black arrows) in the ascending aorta, with a focal contour abnormality suspicious for aneurysm (white arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial high-pitch nongated CTA image obtained to clarify the pulsation artifact shows this as a high aberrant origin of the right coronary artery (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic" aria-label="Pulsation artifact and high-pitch imaging. (a) Axial CTA image shows pulsation artifact (black arrows) in the ascending aorta, with a focal contour abnormality suspicious for aneurysm (white arrow). (b) Axial high-pitch nongated CTA image obtained to clarify the pulsation artifact shows this as a high aberrant origin of the right coronary artery (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig2b.jpeg" height="1275" width="1309" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Pulsation artifact and high-pitch imaging. <b>(a)</b> Axial CTA image shows pulsation artifact (black arrows) in the ascending aorta, with a focal contour abnormality suspicious for aneurysm (white arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial high-pitch nongated CTA image obtained to clarify the pulsation artifact shows this as a high aberrant origin of the right coronary artery (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic" aria-label="Contained rupture and delayed imaging in a patient after ascending aortic repair, with fungemia and a pulsatile anterior chest wall mass. (a) Axial precontrast CTA image shows a high-attenuation hematoma (arrows) in the anterior mediastinum. Note the mild soft tissue anterior to the sternum and right costochondral cartilage (arrowhead). (b) Axial CTA image shows the ascending aortic lumen compressed by the surrounding apparent soft-tissue abnormality that suggests hematoma (arrow). Soft-tissue stranding surrounds the finding. (c) Axial CTA image obtained with a 70-second delay shows enhancement of the prior soft-tissue area (white arrow) equal to that of the blood pool, consistent with a contained rupture surrounding the graft (black arrow). Blood tracks into the anterior chest wall, a finding consistent with an aortocutaneous fistula (red arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig3a.jpeg" height="1224" width="1238" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Contained rupture and delayed imaging in a patient after ascending aortic repair, with fungemia and a pulsatile anterior chest wall mass. <b>(a)</b> Axial precontrast CTA image shows a high-attenuation hematoma (arrows) in the anterior mediastinum. Note the mild soft tissue anterior to the sternum and right costochondral cartilage (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial CTA image shows the ascending aortic lumen compressed by the surrounding apparent soft-tissue abnormality that suggests hematoma (arrow). Soft-tissue stranding surrounds the finding. <b>(c)</b> Axial CTA image obtained with a 70-second delay shows enhancement of the prior soft-tissue area (white arrow) equal to that of the blood pool, consistent with a contained rupture surrounding the graft (black arrow). Blood tracks into the anterior chest wall, a finding consistent with an aortocutaneous fistula (red arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic" aria-label="Contained rupture and delayed imaging in a patient after ascending aortic repair, with fungemia and a pulsatile anterior chest wall mass. (a) Axial precontrast CTA image shows a high-attenuation hematoma (arrows) in the anterior mediastinum. Note the mild soft tissue anterior to the sternum and right costochondral cartilage (arrowhead). (b) Axial CTA image shows the ascending aortic lumen compressed by the surrounding apparent soft-tissue abnormality that suggests hematoma (arrow). Soft-tissue stranding surrounds the finding. (c) Axial CTA image obtained with a 70-second delay shows enhancement of the prior soft-tissue area (white arrow) equal to that of the blood pool, consistent with a contained rupture surrounding the graft (black arrow). Blood tracks into the anterior chest wall, a finding consistent with an aortocutaneous fistula (red arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig3b.jpeg" height="1224" width="1231" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Contained rupture and delayed imaging in a patient after ascending aortic repair, with fungemia and a pulsatile anterior chest wall mass. <b>(a)</b> Axial precontrast CTA image shows a high-attenuation hematoma (arrows) in the anterior mediastinum. Note the mild soft tissue anterior to the sternum and right costochondral cartilage (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial CTA image shows the ascending aortic lumen compressed by the surrounding apparent soft-tissue abnormality that suggests hematoma (arrow). Soft-tissue stranding surrounds the finding. <b>(c)</b> Axial CTA image obtained with a 70-second delay shows enhancement of the prior soft-tissue area (white arrow) equal to that of the blood pool, consistent with a contained rupture surrounding the graft (black arrow). Blood tracks into the anterior chest wall, a finding consistent with an aortocutaneous fistula (red arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic" aria-label="Contained rupture and delayed imaging in a patient after ascending aortic repair, with fungemia and a pulsatile anterior chest wall mass. (a) Axial precontrast CTA image shows a high-attenuation hematoma (arrows) in the anterior mediastinum. Note the mild soft tissue anterior to the sternum and right costochondral cartilage (arrowhead). (b) Axial CTA image shows the ascending aortic lumen compressed by the surrounding apparent soft-tissue abnormality that suggests hematoma (arrow). Soft-tissue stranding surrounds the finding. (c) Axial CTA image obtained with a 70-second delay shows enhancement of the prior soft-tissue area (white arrow) equal to that of the blood pool, consistent with a contained rupture surrounding the graft (black arrow). Blood tracks into the anterior chest wall, a finding consistent with an aortocutaneous fistula (red arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig3c.jpeg" height="1224" width="1230" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Contained rupture and delayed imaging in a patient after ascending aortic repair, with fungemia and a pulsatile anterior chest wall mass. <b>(a)</b> Axial precontrast CTA image shows a high-attenuation hematoma (arrows) in the anterior mediastinum. Note the mild soft tissue anterior to the sternum and right costochondral cartilage (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial CTA image shows the ascending aortic lumen compressed by the surrounding apparent soft-tissue abnormality that suggests hematoma (arrow). Soft-tissue stranding surrounds the finding. <b>(c)</b> Axial CTA image obtained with a 70-second delay shows enhancement of the prior soft-tissue area (white arrow) equal to that of the blood pool, consistent with a contained rupture surrounding the graft (black arrow). Blood tracks into the anterior chest wall, a finding consistent with an aortocutaneous fistula (red arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic" aria-label="Type B dissection with horizontal entry tear. A false lumen (*) is located superior and lateral to the true lumen. (a) Left anterior oblique 2-mm multiplanar reformation shows an entry tear (arrow) communicating with a false lumen. The false lumen is opacified better than the true lumen. (b) Axial 2-mm image shows the entry tear (arrow), which is not as well visualized and would not be evident on one axial image."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig4a.jpeg" height="1192" width="1143" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Type B dissection with horizontal entry tear. A false lumen (*) is located superior and lateral to the true lumen. <b>(a)</b> Left anterior oblique 2-mm multiplanar reformation shows an entry tear (arrow) communicating with a false lumen. The false lumen is opacified better than the true lumen. <b>(b)</b> Axial 2-mm image shows the entry tear (arrow), which is not as well visualized and would not be evident on one axial image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic" aria-label="Type B dissection with horizontal entry tear. A false lumen (*) is located superior and lateral to the true lumen. (a) Left anterior oblique 2-mm multiplanar reformation shows an entry tear (arrow) communicating with a false lumen. The false lumen is opacified better than the true lumen. (b) Axial 2-mm image shows the entry tear (arrow), which is not as well visualized and would not be evident on one axial image."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig4b.jpeg" height="1192" width="1507" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Type B dissection with horizontal entry tear. A false lumen (*) is located superior and lateral to the true lumen. <b>(a)</b> Left anterior oblique 2-mm multiplanar reformation shows an entry tear (arrow) communicating with a false lumen. The false lumen is opacified better than the true lumen. <b>(b)</b> Axial 2-mm image shows the entry tear (arrow), which is not as well visualized and would not be evident on one axial image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic" aria-label="Dual-energy CTA for evaluating postoperative changes. (a) Axial weighted-average CTA image derived from both low- and high–kilovolt peak image data shows a high-attenuation felt ring, peripheral to circumferential low attenuation (arrows), representing a graft end. (b) Axial VNC image, obtained after intravenous contrast material was removed shows that circumferential high-attenuation persists and is consistent with a felt ring placed at the ascending aortic graft anastomosis. The inner ring (arrows) has lower attenuation yet has mildly higher attenuation than that of the lumen."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig5a.jpeg" height="1539" width="1328" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Dual-energy CTA for evaluating postoperative changes. <b>(a)</b> Axial weighted-average CTA image derived from both low- and high–kilovolt peak image data shows a high-attenuation felt ring, peripheral to circumferential low attenuation (arrows), representing a graft end. <b>(b)</b> Axial VNC image, obtained after intravenous contrast material was removed shows that circumferential high-attenuation persists and is consistent with a felt ring placed at the ascending aortic graft anastomosis. The inner ring (arrows) has lower attenuation yet has mildly higher attenuation than that of the lumen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic" aria-label="Dual-energy CTA for evaluating postoperative changes. (a) Axial weighted-average CTA image derived from both low- and high–kilovolt peak image data shows a high-attenuation felt ring, peripheral to circumferential low attenuation (arrows), representing a graft end. (b) Axial VNC image, obtained after intravenous contrast material was removed shows that circumferential high-attenuation persists and is consistent with a felt ring placed at the ascending aortic graft anastomosis. The inner ring (arrows) has lower attenuation yet has mildly higher attenuation than that of the lumen."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig5b.jpeg" height="1539" width="1322" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Dual-energy CTA for evaluating postoperative changes. <b>(a)</b> Axial weighted-average CTA image derived from both low- and high–kilovolt peak image data shows a high-attenuation felt ring, peripheral to circumferential low attenuation (arrows), representing a graft end. <b>(b)</b> Axial VNC image, obtained after intravenous contrast material was removed shows that circumferential high-attenuation persists and is consistent with a felt ring placed at the ascending aortic graft anastomosis. The inner ring (arrows) has lower attenuation yet has mildly higher attenuation than that of the lumen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic" aria-label="Pulsation artifact on a dual-energy CT VNC image. (a) Axial dual-energy VNC CT image shows high-attenuation ring artifacts in the anterior and posterior ascending aorta from pulsation, which can simulate apparent acute intramural hematoma (arrows). The aorta is displaced during imaging, and thus two lines each are seen in areas of artifact. (b) Corresponding axial dual-energy CT image shows pulsation artifact (arrows). For this reason, dual-energy CT is not used in the evaluation for acute aortic syndromes."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig6a.jpeg" height="1303" width="1328" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Pulsation artifact on a dual-energy CT VNC image. <b>(a)</b> Axial dual-energy VNC CT image shows high-attenuation ring artifacts in the anterior and posterior ascending aorta from pulsation, which can simulate apparent acute intramural hematoma (arrows). The aorta is displaced during imaging, and thus two lines each are seen in areas of artifact. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding axial dual-energy CT image shows pulsation artifact (arrows). For this reason, dual-energy CT is not used in the evaluation for acute aortic syndromes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic" aria-label="Pulsation artifact on a dual-energy CT VNC image. (a) Axial dual-energy VNC CT image shows high-attenuation ring artifacts in the anterior and posterior ascending aorta from pulsation, which can simulate apparent acute intramural hematoma (arrows). The aorta is displaced during imaging, and thus two lines each are seen in areas of artifact. (b) Corresponding axial dual-energy CT image shows pulsation artifact (arrows). For this reason, dual-energy CT is not used in the evaluation for acute aortic syndromes."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig6b.jpeg" height="1303" width="1322" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Pulsation artifact on a dual-energy CT VNC image. <b>(a)</b> Axial dual-energy VNC CT image shows high-attenuation ring artifacts in the anterior and posterior ascending aorta from pulsation, which can simulate apparent acute intramural hematoma (arrows). The aorta is displaced during imaging, and thus two lines each are seen in areas of artifact. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding axial dual-energy CT image shows pulsation artifact (arrows). For this reason, dual-energy CT is not used in the evaluation for acute aortic syndromes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic" aria-label="Retrospective ECG-gating artifact. Coronal multiplanar reconstruction (MPR) from retrospectively ECG-gated CTA in a patient with premature ventricular contractions shows bands (arrows) of artifact, introduced during image acquisition, resulting in incomplete data in certain parts of the cardiac cycle. Data from irregular beats can sometimes be removed or edited, depending on the CT scanner manufacturer."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig7.jpeg" height="1230" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. Retrospective ECG-gating artifact. Coronal multiplanar reconstruction (MPR) from retrospectively ECG-gated CTA in a patient with premature ventricular contractions shows bands (arrows) of artifact, introduced during image acquisition, resulting in incomplete data in certain parts of the cardiac cycle. Data from irregular beats can sometimes be removed or edited, depending on the CT scanner manufacturer.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic" aria-label="Slow flow of false lumen mimicking thrombus. (a) Axial arterial phase CTA image shows low attenuation in the anterior false lumen related to contrast material mixing with unopacified blood (smoke). The contrast material is more dependent in the lumen relative to the unopacified blood. (b) Axial delayed arterial phase CTA image obtained 1 minute later shows homogeneous opacification."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig8a.jpeg" height="1377" width="1278" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Slow flow of false lumen mimicking thrombus. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase CTA image shows low attenuation in the anterior false lumen related to contrast material mixing with unopacified blood (smoke). The contrast material is more dependent in the lumen relative to the unopacified blood. <b>(b)</b> Axial delayed arterial phase CTA image obtained 1 minute later shows homogeneous opacification.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic" aria-label="Slow flow of false lumen mimicking thrombus. (a) Axial arterial phase CTA image shows low attenuation in the anterior false lumen related to contrast material mixing with unopacified blood (smoke). The contrast material is more dependent in the lumen relative to the unopacified blood. (b) Axial delayed arterial phase CTA image obtained 1 minute later shows homogeneous opacification."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig8b.jpeg" height="1377" width="1372" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Slow flow of false lumen mimicking thrombus. <b>(a)</b> Axial arterial phase CTA image shows low attenuation in the anterior false lumen related to contrast material mixing with unopacified blood (smoke). The contrast material is more dependent in the lumen relative to the unopacified blood. <b>(b)</b> Axial delayed arterial phase CTA image obtained 1 minute later shows homogeneous opacification.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic" aria-label="Aortic dissection. Longitudinal photomicrograph shows a thrombus that formed in the false lumen in the media of the artery. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×20.) Fibrosis is depicted in the adventitia. (Courtesy of Navneet Narula, MD, Department of Pathology, NYU Langone Health, New York, NY.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig9.jpeg" height="1410" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Aortic dissection. Longitudinal photomicrograph shows a thrombus that formed in the false lumen in the media of the artery. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×20.) Fibrosis is depicted in the adventitia. (Courtesy of Navneet Narula, MD, Department of Pathology, NYU Langone Health, New York, NY.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic" aria-label="Stanford classification of classic dissection. (a) Sagittal oblique MPR image from CTA performed with a high-pitch technique shows a Stanford type A dissection (arrow), which involves the ascending aorta and is a surgical emergency. The dissection extends to the descending aorta. Given its mobility, the intimomedial flap is blurred in some areas, whereas the remainder of the wall of the aorta is unaffected. (b) Sagittal oblique CTA maximum intensity projection image in a different patient shows a Stanford type B dissection that involves the aorta distal to the distal aspect of the left subclavian orifice (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig10a.jpeg" height="1821" width="1290" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Stanford classification of classic dissection. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal oblique MPR image from CTA performed with a high-pitch technique shows a Stanford type A dissection (arrow), which involves the ascending aorta and is a surgical emergency. The dissection extends to the descending aorta. Given its mobility, the intimomedial flap is blurred in some areas, whereas the remainder of the wall of the aorta is unaffected. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique CTA maximum intensity projection image in a different patient shows a Stanford type B dissection that involves the aorta distal to the distal aspect of the left subclavian orifice (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic" aria-label="Stanford classification of classic dissection. (a) Sagittal oblique MPR image from CTA performed with a high-pitch technique shows a Stanford type A dissection (arrow), which involves the ascending aorta and is a surgical emergency. The dissection extends to the descending aorta. Given its mobility, the intimomedial flap is blurred in some areas, whereas the remainder of the wall of the aorta is unaffected. (b) Sagittal oblique CTA maximum intensity projection image in a different patient shows a Stanford type B dissection that involves the aorta distal to the distal aspect of the left subclavian orifice (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig10b.jpeg" height="1821" width="1360" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Stanford classification of classic dissection. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal oblique MPR image from CTA performed with a high-pitch technique shows a Stanford type A dissection (arrow), which involves the ascending aorta and is a surgical emergency. The dissection extends to the descending aorta. Given its mobility, the intimomedial flap is blurred in some areas, whereas the remainder of the wall of the aorta is unaffected. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal oblique CTA maximum intensity projection image in a different patient shows a Stanford type B dissection that involves the aorta distal to the distal aspect of the left subclavian orifice (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic" aria-label="Type B dissection with arch involvement. (a) Left anterior oblique MPR image shows a thrombosed dissection lumen (arrow) involving the arch just distal to the distal aspect of the origin of the left common carotid artery (arrowhead). (b) Off-axis coronal image shows soft tissue representing a thrombosed classic dissection lumen proximal (arrowhead) and distal (arrow) to the left subclavian artery orifice. (c) Axial MPR image shows an intimal tear (arrow) in the proximal descending aorta, indicating type B dissection, with presumed retrograde extension."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig11a.jpeg" height="1522" width="1279" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Type B dissection with arch involvement. <b>(a)</b> Left anterior oblique MPR image shows a thrombosed dissection lumen (arrow) involving the arch just distal to the distal aspect of the origin of the left common carotid artery (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Off-axis coronal image shows soft tissue representing a thrombosed classic dissection lumen proximal (arrowhead) and distal (arrow) to the left subclavian artery orifice. <b>(c)</b> Axial MPR image shows an intimal tear (arrow) in the proximal descending aorta, indicating type B dissection, with presumed retrograde extension.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic" aria-label="Type B dissection with arch involvement. (a) Left anterior oblique MPR image shows a thrombosed dissection lumen (arrow) involving the arch just distal to the distal aspect of the origin of the left common carotid artery (arrowhead). (b) Off-axis coronal image shows soft tissue representing a thrombosed classic dissection lumen proximal (arrowhead) and distal (arrow) to the left subclavian artery orifice. (c) Axial MPR image shows an intimal tear (arrow) in the proximal descending aorta, indicating type B dissection, with presumed retrograde extension."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig11b.jpeg" height="1522" width="1173" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Type B dissection with arch involvement. <b>(a)</b> Left anterior oblique MPR image shows a thrombosed dissection lumen (arrow) involving the arch just distal to the distal aspect of the origin of the left common carotid artery (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Off-axis coronal image shows soft tissue representing a thrombosed classic dissection lumen proximal (arrowhead) and distal (arrow) to the left subclavian artery orifice. <b>(c)</b> Axial MPR image shows an intimal tear (arrow) in the proximal descending aorta, indicating type B dissection, with presumed retrograde extension.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic" aria-label="Type B dissection with arch involvement. (a) Left anterior oblique MPR image shows a thrombosed dissection lumen (arrow) involving the arch just distal to the distal aspect of the origin of the left common carotid artery (arrowhead). (b) Off-axis coronal image shows soft tissue representing a thrombosed classic dissection lumen proximal (arrowhead) and distal (arrow) to the left subclavian artery orifice. (c) Axial MPR image shows an intimal tear (arrow) in the proximal descending aorta, indicating type B dissection, with presumed retrograde extension."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig11c.jpeg" height="1522" width="1248" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Type B dissection with arch involvement. <b>(a)</b> Left anterior oblique MPR image shows a thrombosed dissection lumen (arrow) involving the arch just distal to the distal aspect of the origin of the left common carotid artery (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Off-axis coronal image shows soft tissue representing a thrombosed classic dissection lumen proximal (arrowhead) and distal (arrow) to the left subclavian artery orifice. <b>(c)</b> Axial MPR image shows an intimal tear (arrow) in the proximal descending aorta, indicating type B dissection, with presumed retrograde extension.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic" aria-label="Intimomedial rupture sign. Axial CTA image shows a type A dissection with an intimal tear located in the aortic arch. The flaps of the intimal tear (arrows) point toward the false lumen, which surrounds the true lumen (*). In the ascending aorta, the false lumen is partially thrombosed (not shown). It is unclear whether a prior dissection flap has sealed or whether retrograde dissection has occurred."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig12.jpeg" height="1317" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Intimomedial rupture sign. Axial CTA image shows a type A dissection with an intimal tear located in the aortic arch. The flaps of the intimal tear (arrows) point toward the false lumen, which surrounds the true lumen (*). In the ascending aorta, the false lumen is partially thrombosed (not shown). It is unclear whether a prior dissection flap has sealed or whether retrograde dissection has occurred.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic" aria-label="Static and dynamic obstruction. (a) Axial CTA image shows an abdominal aortic dissection resulting in both static and dynamic obstruction of the superior mesenteric artery. The aortic dissection of the true lumen is completely collapsed (black arrow). A portion of the dissection flap (white arrow) extends into the proximal superior mesenteric artery, with adjacent thrombus, resulting in complete static or fixed obstruction, and a portion of the collapsed true lumen flap results in dynamic obstruction, overlying the origin. The patient developed small bowel ischemia as a result. Infarcts (arrowhead) are depicted in the right kidney. (b) Axial CTA image in another patient shows severe right kidney hypoperfusion (white arrow), due to dynamic obstruction of the right renal artery ostium from the collapsed true lumen (black arrow), with the dissection flap lying like a cloth over the renal artery ostium, indicating intermittent obstruction. Note the relative nonenhancement of the right renal vein in comparison with that of the left renal vein, from delayed venous return. A patent right renal artery is depicted distal to the orifice, and the left kidney has normal perfusion."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig13a.jpeg" height="952" width="1522" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Static and dynamic obstruction. <b>(a)</b> Axial CTA image shows an abdominal aortic dissection resulting in both static and dynamic obstruction of the superior mesenteric artery. The aortic dissection of the true lumen is completely collapsed (black arrow). A portion of the dissection flap (white arrow) extends into the proximal superior mesenteric artery, with adjacent thrombus, resulting in complete static or fixed obstruction, and a portion of the collapsed true lumen flap results in dynamic obstruction, overlying the origin. The patient developed small bowel ischemia as a result. Infarcts (arrowhead) are depicted in the right kidney. <b>(b)</b> Axial CTA image in another patient shows severe right kidney hypoperfusion (white arrow), due to dynamic obstruction of the right renal artery ostium from the collapsed true lumen (black arrow), with the dissection flap lying like a cloth over the renal artery ostium, indicating intermittent obstruction. Note the relative nonenhancement of the right renal vein in comparison with that of the left renal vein, from delayed venous return. A patent right renal artery is depicted distal to the orifice, and the left kidney has normal perfusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic" aria-label="Static and dynamic obstruction. (a) Axial CTA image shows an abdominal aortic dissection resulting in both static and dynamic obstruction of the superior mesenteric artery. The aortic dissection of the true lumen is completely collapsed (black arrow). A portion of the dissection flap (white arrow) extends into the proximal superior mesenteric artery, with adjacent thrombus, resulting in complete static or fixed obstruction, and a portion of the collapsed true lumen flap results in dynamic obstruction, overlying the origin. The patient developed small bowel ischemia as a result. Infarcts (arrowhead) are depicted in the right kidney. (b) Axial CTA image in another patient shows severe right kidney hypoperfusion (white arrow), due to dynamic obstruction of the right renal artery ostium from the collapsed true lumen (black arrow), with the dissection flap lying like a cloth over the renal artery ostium, indicating intermittent obstruction. Note the relative nonenhancement of the right renal vein in comparison with that of the left renal vein, from delayed venous return. A patent right renal artery is depicted distal to the orifice, and the left kidney has normal perfusion."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig13b.jpeg" height="952" width="1428" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Static and dynamic obstruction. <b>(a)</b> Axial CTA image shows an abdominal aortic dissection resulting in both static and dynamic obstruction of the superior mesenteric artery. The aortic dissection of the true lumen is completely collapsed (black arrow). A portion of the dissection flap (white arrow) extends into the proximal superior mesenteric artery, with adjacent thrombus, resulting in complete static or fixed obstruction, and a portion of the collapsed true lumen flap results in dynamic obstruction, overlying the origin. The patient developed small bowel ischemia as a result. Infarcts (arrowhead) are depicted in the right kidney. <b>(b)</b> Axial CTA image in another patient shows severe right kidney hypoperfusion (white arrow), due to dynamic obstruction of the right renal artery ostium from the collapsed true lumen (black arrow), with the dissection flap lying like a cloth over the renal artery ostium, indicating intermittent obstruction. Note the relative nonenhancement of the right renal vein in comparison with that of the left renal vein, from delayed venous return. A patent right renal artery is depicted distal to the orifice, and the left kidney has normal perfusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic" aria-label="Natural history of classic dissection. (a, b) Axial CT images show regression of aortic dissection, as depicted on the initial CT image (a) and the image obtained after 2 years (b). (c, d) Sagittal oblique CT images in a different patient show dissection on the initial CT image (c), with the false lumen superiorly located relative to the true lumen, which enlarged after 2 weeks (d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig14a.jpeg" height="1167" width="1340" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Natural history of classic dissection. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT images show regression of aortic dissection, as depicted on the initial CT image <b>(a)</b> and the image obtained after 2 years <b>(b)</b>. <b>(c, d)</b> Sagittal oblique CT images in a different patient show dissection on the initial CT image <b>(c)</b>, with the false lumen superiorly located relative to the true lumen, which enlarged after 2 weeks <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic" aria-label="Natural history of classic dissection. (a, b) Axial CT images show regression of aortic dissection, as depicted on the initial CT image (a) and the image obtained after 2 years (b). (c, d) Sagittal oblique CT images in a different patient show dissection on the initial CT image (c), with the false lumen superiorly located relative to the true lumen, which enlarged after 2 weeks (d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig14b.jpeg" height="1167" width="1310" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Natural history of classic dissection. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT images show regression of aortic dissection, as depicted on the initial CT image <b>(a)</b> and the image obtained after 2 years <b>(b)</b>. <b>(c, d)</b> Sagittal oblique CT images in a different patient show dissection on the initial CT image <b>(c)</b>, with the false lumen superiorly located relative to the true lumen, which enlarged after 2 weeks <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic" aria-label="Natural history of classic dissection. (a, b) Axial CT images show regression of aortic dissection, as depicted on the initial CT image (a) and the image obtained after 2 years (b). (c, d) Sagittal oblique CT images in a different patient show dissection on the initial CT image (c), with the false lumen superiorly located relative to the true lumen, which enlarged after 2 weeks (d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig14c.jpeg" height="1395" width="1346" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. Natural history of classic dissection. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT images show regression of aortic dissection, as depicted on the initial CT image <b>(a)</b> and the image obtained after 2 years <b>(b)</b>. <b>(c, d)</b> Sagittal oblique CT images in a different patient show dissection on the initial CT image <b>(c)</b>, with the false lumen superiorly located relative to the true lumen, which enlarged after 2 weeks <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14d" class="graphic" aria-label="Natural history of classic dissection. (a, b) Axial CT images show regression of aortic dissection, as depicted on the initial CT image (a) and the image obtained after 2 years (b). (c, d) Sagittal oblique CT images in a different patient show dissection on the initial CT image (c), with the false lumen superiorly located relative to the true lumen, which enlarged after 2 weeks (d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig14d.jpeg" height="1394" width="1295" aria-labelledby="fig14d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14d</span>. Natural history of classic dissection. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial CT images show regression of aortic dissection, as depicted on the initial CT image <b>(a)</b> and the image obtained after 2 years <b>(b)</b>. <b>(c, d)</b> Sagittal oblique CT images in a different patient show dissection on the initial CT image <b>(c)</b>, with the false lumen superiorly located relative to the true lumen, which enlarged after 2 weeks <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig14d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic" aria-label="PAU. (a) Off-axial MPR image shows a saccular area of contrast enhancement (white arrow) surrounded by an IMH (arrowheads). The PAU is located adjacent to calcified plaque and mild soft tissue (black arrow) that is a combination of IMH and noncalcified plaque. (b) Off-coronal maximum intensity projection image also shows a saccular area (arrow), atherosclerotic disease in the aorta, and a longitudinal IMH (arrowheads)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig15a.jpeg" height="1260" width="1286" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. PAU. <b>(a)</b> Off-axial MPR image shows a saccular area of contrast enhancement (white arrow) surrounded by an IMH (arrowheads). The PAU is located adjacent to calcified plaque and mild soft tissue (black arrow) that is a combination of IMH and noncalcified plaque. <b>(b)</b> Off-coronal maximum intensity projection image also shows a saccular area (arrow), atherosclerotic disease in the aorta, and a longitudinal IMH (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic" aria-label="PAU. (a) Off-axial MPR image shows a saccular area of contrast enhancement (white arrow) surrounded by an IMH (arrowheads). The PAU is located adjacent to calcified plaque and mild soft tissue (black arrow) that is a combination of IMH and noncalcified plaque. (b) Off-coronal maximum intensity projection image also shows a saccular area (arrow), atherosclerotic disease in the aorta, and a longitudinal IMH (arrowheads)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig15b.jpeg" height="1260" width="1364" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. PAU. <b>(a)</b> Off-axial MPR image shows a saccular area of contrast enhancement (white arrow) surrounded by an IMH (arrowheads). The PAU is located adjacent to calcified plaque and mild soft tissue (black arrow) that is a combination of IMH and noncalcified plaque. <b>(b)</b> Off-coronal maximum intensity projection image also shows a saccular area (arrow), atherosclerotic disease in the aorta, and a longitudinal IMH (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic" aria-label="Ascending aortic IMH. (a) Axial CTA image shows a smooth interface of wall thickening (arrowheads) with the contrast-enhanced lumen. Note that pericardial fluid (arrow) is depicted in the recess, in addition to the classic dissection in the descending aorta. (b) Axial precontrast CTA image, viewed with narrow soft-tissue windows, better illustrates the crescentic nature of wall thickening (arrowhead) and the high attenuation consistent with type A IMH. The pericardial recess fluid, in contrast, is low-attenuation simple fluid (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig16a.jpeg" height="1294" width="1316" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Ascending aortic IMH. <b>(a)</b> Axial CTA image shows a smooth interface of wall thickening (arrowheads) with the contrast-enhanced lumen. Note that pericardial fluid (arrow) is depicted in the recess, in addition to the classic dissection in the descending aorta. <b>(b)</b> Axial precontrast CTA image, viewed with narrow soft-tissue windows, better illustrates the crescentic nature of wall thickening (arrowhead) and the high attenuation consistent with type A IMH. The pericardial recess fluid, in contrast, is low-attenuation simple fluid (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic" aria-label="Ascending aortic IMH. (a) Axial CTA image shows a smooth interface of wall thickening (arrowheads) with the contrast-enhanced lumen. Note that pericardial fluid (arrow) is depicted in the recess, in addition to the classic dissection in the descending aorta. (b) Axial precontrast CTA image, viewed with narrow soft-tissue windows, better illustrates the crescentic nature of wall thickening (arrowhead) and the high attenuation consistent with type A IMH. The pericardial recess fluid, in contrast, is low-attenuation simple fluid (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig16b.jpeg" height="1294" width="1334" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Ascending aortic IMH. <b>(a)</b> Axial CTA image shows a smooth interface of wall thickening (arrowheads) with the contrast-enhanced lumen. Note that pericardial fluid (arrow) is depicted in the recess, in addition to the classic dissection in the descending aorta. <b>(b)</b> Axial precontrast CTA image, viewed with narrow soft-tissue windows, better illustrates the crescentic nature of wall thickening (arrowhead) and the high attenuation consistent with type A IMH. The pericardial recess fluid, in contrast, is low-attenuation simple fluid (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic" aria-label="Varying outcomes of IMH in two patients. (a) Axial precontrast (top left) and postcontrast (bottom left) images from initial CTA were reassessed with chest CTA images obtained 5 months later without (top right) and with (bottom right) contrast material. The initial CTA image (top left) shows a mild high-attenuation acute IMH, with intimal calcification displacement toward the lumen, which decreased in thickness (bottom right) and became isoattenuating (top right) 5 months later, consistent with regression. (b) Axial CTA images in a different patient show an acute high-attenuation IMH (arrows) on the initial image (left). The IMH is more isoattenuating on the 1-month follow-up image (center), yet the mild persistent high attenuation and greater IMH thickness suggest interval rebleeding. The conversion to a classic dissection with a false luminal flow occurred at 4 months (right) after the initial appearance at CTA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig17a.jpeg" height="2604" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Varying outcomes of IMH in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial precontrast (top left) and postcontrast (bottom left) images from initial CTA were reassessed with chest CTA images obtained 5 months later without (top right) and with (bottom right) contrast material. The initial CTA image (top left) shows a mild high-attenuation acute IMH, with intimal calcification displacement toward the lumen, which decreased in thickness (bottom right) and became isoattenuating (top right) 5 months later, consistent with regression. <b>(b)</b> Axial CTA images in a different patient show an acute high-attenuation IMH (arrows) on the initial image (left). The IMH is more isoattenuating on the 1-month follow-up image (center), yet the mild persistent high attenuation and greater IMH thickness suggest interval rebleeding. The conversion to a classic dissection with a false luminal flow occurred at 4 months (right) after the initial appearance at CTA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic" aria-label="Varying outcomes of IMH in two patients. (a) Axial precontrast (top left) and postcontrast (bottom left) images from initial CTA were reassessed with chest CTA images obtained 5 months later without (top right) and with (bottom right) contrast material. The initial CTA image (top left) shows a mild high-attenuation acute IMH, with intimal calcification displacement toward the lumen, which decreased in thickness (bottom right) and became isoattenuating (top right) 5 months later, consistent with regression. (b) Axial CTA images in a different patient show an acute high-attenuation IMH (arrows) on the initial image (left). The IMH is more isoattenuating on the 1-month follow-up image (center), yet the mild persistent high attenuation and greater IMH thickness suggest interval rebleeding. The conversion to a classic dissection with a false luminal flow occurred at 4 months (right) after the initial appearance at CTA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig17b.jpeg" height="1440" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Varying outcomes of IMH in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial precontrast (top left) and postcontrast (bottom left) images from initial CTA were reassessed with chest CTA images obtained 5 months later without (top right) and with (bottom right) contrast material. The initial CTA image (top left) shows a mild high-attenuation acute IMH, with intimal calcification displacement toward the lumen, which decreased in thickness (bottom right) and became isoattenuating (top right) 5 months later, consistent with regression. <b>(b)</b> Axial CTA images in a different patient show an acute high-attenuation IMH (arrows) on the initial image (left). The IMH is more isoattenuating on the 1-month follow-up image (center), yet the mild persistent high attenuation and greater IMH thickness suggest interval rebleeding. The conversion to a classic dissection with a false luminal flow occurred at 4 months (right) after the initial appearance at CTA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic" aria-label="Aneurysm rupture. Axial nonenhanced CT image (a) shows high-attenuation acute thrombus (arrowheads in a) in the outer wall of a large descending aneurysm, indicating impending rupture, adjacent to the inner thrombus (arrow in a), better depicted on the postcontrast axial image (b). The aorta has lost its typical shape and is draped around the spine, probably owing to wall weakening, another sign of impending rupture. Mild soft tissue in the mediastinum indicates rupture (arrows in b). The pleural effusions were not hemorrhagic, although if they were, they would be suspicious for rupture."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig18a.jpeg" height="1308" width="1690" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. Aneurysm rupture. Axial nonenhanced CT image <b>(a)</b> shows high-attenuation acute thrombus (arrowheads in <b>a</b>) in the outer wall of a large descending aneurysm, indicating impending rupture, adjacent to the inner thrombus (arrow in <b>a</b>), better depicted on the postcontrast axial image <b>(b)</b>. The aorta has lost its typical shape and is draped around the spine, probably owing to wall weakening, another sign of impending rupture. Mild soft tissue in the mediastinum indicates rupture (arrows in <b>b</b>). The pleural effusions were not hemorrhagic, although if they were, they would be suspicious for rupture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic" aria-label="Aneurysm rupture. Axial nonenhanced CT image (a) shows high-attenuation acute thrombus (arrowheads in a) in the outer wall of a large descending aneurysm, indicating impending rupture, adjacent to the inner thrombus (arrow in a), better depicted on the postcontrast axial image (b). The aorta has lost its typical shape and is draped around the spine, probably owing to wall weakening, another sign of impending rupture. Mild soft tissue in the mediastinum indicates rupture (arrows in b). The pleural effusions were not hemorrhagic, although if they were, they would be suspicious for rupture."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig18b.jpeg" height="1308" width="1660" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. Aneurysm rupture. Axial nonenhanced CT image <b>(a)</b> shows high-attenuation acute thrombus (arrowheads in <b>a</b>) in the outer wall of a large descending aneurysm, indicating impending rupture, adjacent to the inner thrombus (arrow in <b>a</b>), better depicted on the postcontrast axial image <b>(b)</b>. The aorta has lost its typical shape and is draped around the spine, probably owing to wall weakening, another sign of impending rupture. Mild soft tissue in the mediastinum indicates rupture (arrows in <b>b</b>). The pleural effusions were not hemorrhagic, although if they were, they would be suspicious for rupture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic" aria-label="IMH with development of ULP. (a) Left anterior oblique MPR image shows an IMH (arrowheads), with a small aortic arch ULP (arrow) extending from the superior lumen into the IMH. Given the location, ULP can be difficult to appreciate on axial images. (b) Left anterior oblique MPR image obtained 3 months later shows that the IMH thickness has decreased (arrowheads), yet the ULP (arrow) has enlarged, with a bilobed appearance."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig19a.jpeg" height="1519" width="1240" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. IMH with development of ULP. <b>(a)</b> Left anterior oblique MPR image shows an IMH (arrowheads), with a small aortic arch ULP (arrow) extending from the superior lumen into the IMH. Given the location, ULP can be difficult to appreciate on axial images. <b>(b)</b> Left anterior oblique MPR image obtained 3 months later shows that the IMH thickness has decreased (arrowheads), yet the ULP (arrow) has enlarged, with a bilobed appearance.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic" aria-label="IMH with development of ULP. (a) Left anterior oblique MPR image shows an IMH (arrowheads), with a small aortic arch ULP (arrow) extending from the superior lumen into the IMH. Given the location, ULP can be difficult to appreciate on axial images. (b) Left anterior oblique MPR image obtained 3 months later shows that the IMH thickness has decreased (arrowheads), yet the ULP (arrow) has enlarged, with a bilobed appearance."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig19b.jpeg" height="1519" width="1410" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. IMH with development of ULP. <b>(a)</b> Left anterior oblique MPR image shows an IMH (arrowheads), with a small aortic arch ULP (arrow) extending from the superior lumen into the IMH. Given the location, ULP can be difficult to appreciate on axial images. <b>(b)</b> Left anterior oblique MPR image obtained 3 months later shows that the IMH thickness has decreased (arrowheads), yet the ULP (arrow) has enlarged, with a bilobed appearance.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic" aria-label="Illustrations show PAU, ULP, and intramural blood pool (IMBP). (a) A PAU occurs in the area of atherosclerosis and has a broad communication with the lumen (light gray area, red arrow), with typically an undulating surface along the lumen wall owing to soft-tissue noncalcified plaque and intimal thrombus (dark gray area, black straight arrows) and calcified plaque (white arrows). Crescentic IMH is also present in the wall (dark gray area, curved arrows). (b) A ULP is a broadly communicating saccular area (light gray area, arrowhead) that also disrupts the intima and is seen in the IMH (dark gray area). The white intima is disrupted by the ULP. Crescentic soft tissue in the aortic wall refers to the IMH, which has a smooth lumen-wall interface. (c) IMBP (arrowhead) within the IMH (dark gray area) in the media has either no or minimal visualized communication with the aortic lumen. Communication of the IMBP with an intercostal or bronchial artery (arrow) is helpful in differentiation."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig20a.jpeg" height="1096" width="1130" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. Illustrations show PAU, ULP, and intramural blood pool (IMBP). <b>(a)</b> A PAU occurs in the area of atherosclerosis and has a broad communication with the lumen (light gray area, red arrow), with typically an undulating surface along the lumen wall owing to soft-tissue noncalcified plaque and intimal thrombus (dark gray area, black straight arrows) and calcified plaque (white arrows). Crescentic IMH is also present in the wall (dark gray area, curved arrows). <b>(b)</b> A ULP is a broadly communicating saccular area (light gray area, arrowhead) that also disrupts the intima and is seen in the IMH (dark gray area). The white intima is disrupted by the ULP. Crescentic soft tissue in the aortic wall refers to the IMH, which has a smooth lumen-wall interface. <b>(c)</b> IMBP (arrowhead) within the IMH (dark gray area) in the media has either no or minimal visualized communication with the aortic lumen. Communication of the IMBP with an intercostal or bronchial artery (arrow) is helpful in differentiation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic" aria-label="Illustrations show PAU, ULP, and intramural blood pool (IMBP). (a) A PAU occurs in the area of atherosclerosis and has a broad communication with the lumen (light gray area, red arrow), with typically an undulating surface along the lumen wall owing to soft-tissue noncalcified plaque and intimal thrombus (dark gray area, black straight arrows) and calcified plaque (white arrows). Crescentic IMH is also present in the wall (dark gray area, curved arrows). (b) A ULP is a broadly communicating saccular area (light gray area, arrowhead) that also disrupts the intima and is seen in the IMH (dark gray area). The white intima is disrupted by the ULP. Crescentic soft tissue in the aortic wall refers to the IMH, which has a smooth lumen-wall interface. (c) IMBP (arrowhead) within the IMH (dark gray area) in the media has either no or minimal visualized communication with the aortic lumen. Communication of the IMBP with an intercostal or bronchial artery (arrow) is helpful in differentiation."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig20b.jpeg" height="1109" width="841" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. Illustrations show PAU, ULP, and intramural blood pool (IMBP). <b>(a)</b> A PAU occurs in the area of atherosclerosis and has a broad communication with the lumen (light gray area, red arrow), with typically an undulating surface along the lumen wall owing to soft-tissue noncalcified plaque and intimal thrombus (dark gray area, black straight arrows) and calcified plaque (white arrows). Crescentic IMH is also present in the wall (dark gray area, curved arrows). <b>(b)</b> A ULP is a broadly communicating saccular area (light gray area, arrowhead) that also disrupts the intima and is seen in the IMH (dark gray area). The white intima is disrupted by the ULP. Crescentic soft tissue in the aortic wall refers to the IMH, which has a smooth lumen-wall interface. <b>(c)</b> IMBP (arrowhead) within the IMH (dark gray area) in the media has either no or minimal visualized communication with the aortic lumen. Communication of the IMBP with an intercostal or bronchial artery (arrow) is helpful in differentiation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20c" class="graphic" aria-label="Illustrations show PAU, ULP, and intramural blood pool (IMBP). (a) A PAU occurs in the area of atherosclerosis and has a broad communication with the lumen (light gray area, red arrow), with typically an undulating surface along the lumen wall owing to soft-tissue noncalcified plaque and intimal thrombus (dark gray area, black straight arrows) and calcified plaque (white arrows). Crescentic IMH is also present in the wall (dark gray area, curved arrows). (b) A ULP is a broadly communicating saccular area (light gray area, arrowhead) that also disrupts the intima and is seen in the IMH (dark gray area). The white intima is disrupted by the ULP. Crescentic soft tissue in the aortic wall refers to the IMH, which has a smooth lumen-wall interface. (c) IMBP (arrowhead) within the IMH (dark gray area) in the media has either no or minimal visualized communication with the aortic lumen. Communication of the IMBP with an intercostal or bronchial artery (arrow) is helpful in differentiation."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig20c.jpeg" height="1106" width="901" aria-labelledby="fig20c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20c</span>. Illustrations show PAU, ULP, and intramural blood pool (IMBP). <b>(a)</b> A PAU occurs in the area of atherosclerosis and has a broad communication with the lumen (light gray area, red arrow), with typically an undulating surface along the lumen wall owing to soft-tissue noncalcified plaque and intimal thrombus (dark gray area, black straight arrows) and calcified plaque (white arrows). Crescentic IMH is also present in the wall (dark gray area, curved arrows). <b>(b)</b> A ULP is a broadly communicating saccular area (light gray area, arrowhead) that also disrupts the intima and is seen in the IMH (dark gray area). The white intima is disrupted by the ULP. Crescentic soft tissue in the aortic wall refers to the IMH, which has a smooth lumen-wall interface. <b>(c)</b> IMBP (arrowhead) within the IMH (dark gray area) in the media has either no or minimal visualized communication with the aortic lumen. Communication of the IMBP with an intercostal or bronchial artery (arrow) is helpful in differentiation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig20c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic" aria-label="IMBP. (a) Coronal CTA image shows IMBP as a contrast material collection (white arrow) in the IMH (black arrows) that communicates with an intercostal artery (arrowhead). (b) Oblique CTA image shows a small connection with the lumen of the aorta (arrow). Note the left intercostal artery (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig21a.jpeg" height="1089" width="1264" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span>. IMBP. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CTA image shows IMBP as a contrast material collection (white arrow) in the IMH (black arrows) that communicates with an intercostal artery (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Oblique CTA image shows a small connection with the lumen of the aorta (arrow). Note the left intercostal artery (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic" aria-label="IMBP. (a) Coronal CTA image shows IMBP as a contrast material collection (white arrow) in the IMH (black arrows) that communicates with an intercostal artery (arrowhead). (b) Oblique CTA image shows a small connection with the lumen of the aorta (arrow). Note the left intercostal artery (arrowhead)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig21b.jpeg" height="1089" width="1385" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span>. IMBP. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CTA image shows IMBP as a contrast material collection (white arrow) in the IMH (black arrows) that communicates with an intercostal artery (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Oblique CTA image shows a small connection with the lumen of the aorta (arrow). Note the left intercostal artery (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic" aria-label="Thrombus in an aneurysm. (a) Sagittal left anterior oblique MPR image shows an aneurysm with a low-attenuation mural thrombus, with a mild undulating contour with calcifications in the periphery. (b) Sagittal left anterior oblique MPR image shows the thrombus with an internally located calcification (arrow) in the aneurysmal aorta. The undulating contour and aneurysmal aorta support that the finding is a thrombus."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig22a.jpeg" height="1348" width="1277" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span>. Thrombus in an aneurysm. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal left anterior oblique MPR image shows an aneurysm with a low-attenuation mural thrombus, with a mild undulating contour with calcifications in the periphery. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal left anterior oblique MPR image shows the thrombus with an internally located calcification (arrow) in the aneurysmal aorta. The undulating contour and aneurysmal aorta support that the finding is a thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic" aria-label="Thrombus in an aneurysm. (a) Sagittal left anterior oblique MPR image shows an aneurysm with a low-attenuation mural thrombus, with a mild undulating contour with calcifications in the periphery. (b) Sagittal left anterior oblique MPR image shows the thrombus with an internally located calcification (arrow) in the aneurysmal aorta. The undulating contour and aneurysmal aorta support that the finding is a thrombus."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig22b.jpeg" height="1348" width="1372" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span>. Thrombus in an aneurysm. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal left anterior oblique MPR image shows an aneurysm with a low-attenuation mural thrombus, with a mild undulating contour with calcifications in the periphery. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal left anterior oblique MPR image shows the thrombus with an internally located calcification (arrow) in the aneurysmal aorta. The undulating contour and aneurysmal aorta support that the finding is a thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23" class="graphic" aria-label="Aortic angiosarcoma mimicking thrombus. Axial CTA image shows a filling defect within the thoracic aorta. Note the lobulated contour."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig23.jpeg" height="1525" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span>. Aortic angiosarcoma mimicking thrombus. Axial CTA image shows a filling defect within the thoracic aorta. Note the lobulated contour.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24a" class="graphic" aria-label="Takayasu vasculitis. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image (a) shows circumferential wall thickening in the ascending aorta in a patient with Takayasu arteritis, with mild infiltration of periaortic fat (arrow). FDG activity on the axial PET/CT image (b) localizes to this region, a finding consistent with inflammation."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig24a.jpeg" height="1359" width="1266" aria-labelledby="fig24a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24a</span>. Takayasu vasculitis. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(a)</b> shows circumferential wall thickening in the ascending aorta in a patient with Takayasu arteritis, with mild infiltration of periaortic fat (arrow). FDG activity on the axial PET/CT image <b>(b)</b> localizes to this region, a finding consistent with inflammation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig24a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24b" class="graphic" aria-label="Takayasu vasculitis. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image (a) shows circumferential wall thickening in the ascending aorta in a patient with Takayasu arteritis, with mild infiltration of periaortic fat (arrow). FDG activity on the axial PET/CT image (b) localizes to this region, a finding consistent with inflammation."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig24b.jpeg" height="1359" width="1383" aria-labelledby="fig24b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24b</span>. Takayasu vasculitis. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(a)</b> shows circumferential wall thickening in the ascending aorta in a patient with Takayasu arteritis, with mild infiltration of periaortic fat (arrow). FDG activity on the axial PET/CT image <b>(b)</b> localizes to this region, a finding consistent with inflammation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig24b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25" class="graphic" aria-label="Approach to interpreting aortic wall thickening. This approach aids in the evaluation of the interface of the soft tissue in the aorta with the contrast-enhanced lumen at CTA. +/- = with or without."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig25.jpeg" height="1878" width="3400" aria-labelledby="fig25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25</span>. Approach to interpreting aortic wall thickening. This approach aids in the evaluation of the interface of the soft tissue in the aorta with the contrast-enhanced lumen at CTA. <i>+/-</i> = with or without.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26a" class="graphic" aria-label="Limited intimal tear of the ascending aorta in a 72-year-old man who fell and hurt his chest on a table, with subsequent unrelenting chest pain. (a–f) Axial ECG-gated CT images show a dilated ascending thoracic aorta, with a small subtle intimal flap along the medial aspect of the mid to distal ascending thoracic aorta (arrow in a–e), with focal bulging of the ascending thoracic aorta, which is better appreciated on the coronal oblique reformation (f), in between the small spiraling dissection flaps (arrows in f) (Svensson classification type 3). (g) Left anterior oblique three-dimensional volume-rendered CT image shows the focal outpouching (arrow) of the ascending aortic wall between the small intimal tears of the dissection."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig26a.jpeg" height="833" width="734" aria-labelledby="fig26a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26a</span>. Limited intimal tear of the ascending aorta in a 72-year-old man who fell and hurt his chest on a table, with subsequent unrelenting chest pain. <b>(a–f)</b> Axial ECG-gated CT images show a dilated ascending thoracic aorta, with a small subtle intimal flap along the medial aspect of the mid to distal ascending thoracic aorta (arrow in <b>a–e</b>), with focal bulging of the ascending thoracic aorta, which is better appreciated on the coronal oblique reformation <b>(f)</b>, in between the small spiraling dissection flaps (arrows in <b>f</b>) (Svensson classification type 3). <b>(g)</b> Left anterior oblique three-dimensional volume-rendered CT image shows the focal outpouching (arrow) of the ascending aortic wall between the small intimal tears of the dissection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig26a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26b" class="graphic" aria-label="Limited intimal tear of the ascending aorta in a 72-year-old man who fell and hurt his chest on a table, with subsequent unrelenting chest pain. (a–f) Axial ECG-gated CT images show a dilated ascending thoracic aorta, with a small subtle intimal flap along the medial aspect of the mid to distal ascending thoracic aorta (arrow in a–e), with focal bulging of the ascending thoracic aorta, which is better appreciated on the coronal oblique reformation (f), in between the small spiraling dissection flaps (ar