between the small spiraling dissection flaps (arrows in f) (Svensson classification type 3). (g) Left anterior oblique three-dimensional volume-rendered CT image shows the focal outpouching (arrow) of the ascending aortic wall between the small intimal tears of the dissection."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig26f.jpeg" height="1789" width="1491" aria-labelledby="fig26f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26f</span>. Limited intimal tear of the ascending aorta in a 72-year-old man who fell and hurt his chest on a table, with subsequent unrelenting chest pain. <b>(a–f)</b> Axial ECG-gated CT images show a dilated ascending thoracic aorta, with a small subtle intimal flap along the medial aspect of the mid to distal ascending thoracic aorta (arrow in <b>a–e</b>), with focal bulging of the ascending thoracic aorta, which is better appreciated on the coronal oblique reformation <b>(f)</b>, in between the small spiraling dissection flaps (arrows in <b>f</b>) (Svensson classification type 3). <b>(g)</b> Left anterior oblique three-dimensional volume-rendered CT image shows the focal outpouching (arrow) of the ascending aortic wall between the small intimal tears of the dissection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig26f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26g" class="graphic" aria-label="Limited intimal tear of the ascending aorta in a 72-year-old man who fell and hurt his chest on a table, with subsequent unrelenting chest pain. (a–f) Axial ECG-gated CT images show a dilated ascending thoracic aorta, with a small subtle intimal flap along the medial aspect of the mid to distal ascending thoracic aorta (arrow in a–e), with focal bulging of the ascending thoracic aorta, which is better appreciated on the coronal oblique reformation (f), in between the small spiraling dissection flaps (arrows in f) (Svensson classification type 3). (g) Left anterior oblique three-dimensional volume-rendered CT image shows the focal outpouching (arrow) of the ascending aortic wall between the small intimal tears of the dissection."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig26g.jpeg" height="1789" width="1488" aria-labelledby="fig26g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26g</span>. Limited intimal tear of the ascending aorta in a 72-year-old man who fell and hurt his chest on a table, with subsequent unrelenting chest pain. <b>(a–f)</b> Axial ECG-gated CT images show a dilated ascending thoracic aorta, with a small subtle intimal flap along the medial aspect of the mid to distal ascending thoracic aorta (arrow in <b>a–e</b>), with focal bulging of the ascending thoracic aorta, which is better appreciated on the coronal oblique reformation <b>(f)</b>, in between the small spiraling dissection flaps (arrows in <b>f</b>) (Svensson classification type 3). <b>(g)</b> Left anterior oblique three-dimensional volume-rendered CT image shows the focal outpouching (arrow) of the ascending aortic wall between the small intimal tears of the dissection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig26g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27a" class="graphic" aria-label="Intimointimal intussusception and circumferential ascending aortic dissection in a 50-year-old man with tearing chest pain radiating to the back. (a) Axial CT image shows a folded and serpiginous dissection flap (arrow) in the arch, with a collapsed true lumen. (b) Axial CT image at the mid ascending thoracic aorta shows absence of any dissection flap (*). Note the dissection flap in the descending thoracic aorta, with the collapsed true lumen (arrow). (c) Axial CT image shows linear dissection in the proximal ascending thoracic aorta (black arrows) and a collapsed true lumen in the descending aorta (white arrow). (d) Sagittal oblique MPR image shows the extent of the dissection, with a normal-appearing intervening segment of the ascending aorta (*), which has had the intima stripped from its luminal surface. The intima distally is prolapsing anterogradely into the aortic arch, with a complex folded appearance like a wind sock, resulting in intimointimal intussusception (white arrow). The intima is retrogradely displaced into the aortic root, with an intimal tear in the proximal dissection flap (black arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig27a.jpeg" height="1197" width="1227" aria-labelledby="fig27a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27a</span>. Intimointimal intussusception and circumferential ascending aortic dissection in a 50-year-old man with tearing chest pain radiating to the back. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows a folded and serpiginous dissection flap (arrow) in the arch, with a collapsed true lumen. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image at the mid ascending thoracic aorta shows absence of any dissection flap (*). Note the dissection flap in the descending thoracic aorta, with the collapsed true lumen (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows linear dissection in the proximal ascending thoracic aorta (black arrows) and a collapsed true lumen in the descending aorta (white arrow). <b>(d)</b> Sagittal oblique MPR image shows the extent of the dissection, with a normal-appearing intervening segment of the ascending aorta (*), which has had the intima stripped from its luminal surface. The intima distally is prolapsing anterogradely into the aortic arch, with a complex folded appearance like a wind sock, resulting in intimointimal intussusception (white arrow). The intima is retrogradely displaced into the aortic root, with an intimal tear in the proximal dissection flap (black arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig27a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27b" class="graphic" aria-label="Intimointimal intussusception and circumferential ascending aortic dissection in a 50-year-old man with tearing chest pain radiating to the back. (a) Axial CT image shows a folded and serpiginous dissection flap (arrow) in the arch, with a collapsed true lumen. (b) Axial CT image at the mid ascending thoracic aorta shows absence of any dissection flap (*). Note the dissection flap in the descending thoracic aorta, with the collapsed true lumen (arrow). (c) Axial CT image shows linear dissection in the proximal ascending thoracic aorta (black arrows) and a collapsed true lumen in the descending aorta (white arrow). (d) Sagittal oblique MPR image shows the extent of the dissection, with a normal-appearing intervening segment of the ascending aorta (*), which has had the intima stripped from its luminal surface. The intima distally is prolapsing anterogradely into the aortic arch, with a complex folded appearance like a wind sock, resulting in intimointimal intussusception (white arrow). The intima is retrogradely displaced into the aortic root, with an intimal tear in the proximal dissection flap (black arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig27b.jpeg" height="1197" width="1222" aria-labelledby="fig27b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27b</span>. Intimointimal intussusception and circumferential ascending aortic dissection in a 50-year-old man with tearing chest pain radiating to the back. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows a folded and serpiginous dissection flap (arrow) in the arch, with a collapsed true lumen. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image at the mid ascending thoracic aorta shows absence of any dissection flap (*). Note the dissection flap in the descending thoracic aorta, with the collapsed true lumen (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows linear dissection in the proximal ascending thoracic aorta (black arrows) and a collapsed true lumen in the descending aorta (white arrow). <b>(d)</b> Sagittal oblique MPR image shows the extent of the dissection, with a normal-appearing intervening segment of the ascending aorta (*), which has had the intima stripped from its luminal surface. The intima distally is prolapsing anterogradely into the aortic arch, with a complex folded appearance like a wind sock, resulting in intimointimal intussusception (white arrow). The intima is retrogradely displaced into the aortic root, with an intimal tear in the proximal dissection flap (black arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig27b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27c" class="graphic" aria-label="Intimointimal intussusception and circumferential ascending aortic dissection in a 50-year-old man with tearing chest pain radiating to the back. (a) Axial CT image shows a folded and serpiginous dissection flap (arrow) in the arch, with a collapsed true lumen. (b) Axial CT image at the mid ascending thoracic aorta shows absence of any dissection flap (*). Note the dissection flap in the descending thoracic aorta, with the collapsed true lumen (arrow). (c) Axial CT image shows linear dissection in the proximal ascending thoracic aorta (black arrows) and a collapsed true lumen in the descending aorta (white arrow). (d) Sagittal oblique MPR image shows the extent of the dissection, with a normal-appearing intervening segment of the ascending aorta (*), which has had the intima stripped from its luminal surface. The intima distally is prolapsing anterogradely into the aortic arch, with a complex folded appearance like a wind sock, resulting in intimointimal intussusception (white arrow). The intima is retrogradely displaced into the aortic root, with an intimal tear in the proximal dissection flap (black arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig27c.jpeg" height="1235" width="1266" aria-labelledby="fig27c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27c</span>. Intimointimal intussusception and circumferential ascending aortic dissection in a 50-year-old man with tearing chest pain radiating to the back. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows a folded and serpiginous dissection flap (arrow) in the arch, with a collapsed true lumen. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image at the mid ascending thoracic aorta shows absence of any dissection flap (*). Note the dissection flap in the descending thoracic aorta, with the collapsed true lumen (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows linear dissection in the proximal ascending thoracic aorta (black arrows) and a collapsed true lumen in the descending aorta (white arrow). <b>(d)</b> Sagittal oblique MPR image shows the extent of the dissection, with a normal-appearing intervening segment of the ascending aorta (*), which has had the intima stripped from its luminal surface. The intima distally is prolapsing anterogradely into the aortic arch, with a complex folded appearance like a wind sock, resulting in intimointimal intussusception (white arrow). The intima is retrogradely displaced into the aortic root, with an intimal tear in the proximal dissection flap (black arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig27c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27d" class="graphic" aria-label="Intimointimal intussusception and circumferential ascending aortic dissection in a 50-year-old man with tearing chest pain radiating to the back. (a) Axial CT image shows a folded and serpiginous dissection flap (arrow) in the arch, with a collapsed true lumen. (b) Axial CT image at the mid ascending thoracic aorta shows absence of any dissection flap (*). Note the dissection flap in the descending thoracic aorta, with the collapsed true lumen (arrow). (c) Axial CT image shows linear dissection in the proximal ascending thoracic aorta (black arrows) and a collapsed true lumen in the descending aorta (white arrow). (d) Sagittal oblique MPR image shows the extent of the dissection, with a normal-appearing intervening segment of the ascending aorta (*), which has had the intima stripped from its luminal surface. The intima distally is prolapsing anterogradely into the aortic arch, with a complex folded appearance like a wind sock, resulting in intimointimal intussusception (white arrow). The intima is retrogradely displaced into the aortic root, with an intimal tear in the proximal dissection flap (black arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig27d.jpeg" height="1235" width="1184" aria-labelledby="fig27d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27d</span>. Intimointimal intussusception and circumferential ascending aortic dissection in a 50-year-old man with tearing chest pain radiating to the back. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows a folded and serpiginous dissection flap (arrow) in the arch, with a collapsed true lumen. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image at the mid ascending thoracic aorta shows absence of any dissection flap (*). Note the dissection flap in the descending thoracic aorta, with the collapsed true lumen (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image shows linear dissection in the proximal ascending thoracic aorta (black arrows) and a collapsed true lumen in the descending aorta (white arrow). <b>(d)</b> Sagittal oblique MPR image shows the extent of the dissection, with a normal-appearing intervening segment of the ascending aorta (*), which has had the intima stripped from its luminal surface. The intima distally is prolapsing anterogradely into the aortic arch, with a complex folded appearance like a wind sock, resulting in intimointimal intussusception (white arrow). The intima is retrogradely displaced into the aortic root, with an intimal tear in the proximal dissection flap (black arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig27d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28a" class="graphic" aria-label="Pledget mimicking a pseudoaneurysm and a CPB cannulation site pseudoaneurysm. (a) Postcontrast axial CTA image shows an apparent outpouching (arrow) that can be interpreted as arising from the ascending aorta and potentially a small pseudoaneurysm. (b) Precontrast axial CT image shows the finding with high attenuation, consistent with a pledget (arrow). Note the sternotomy indicating prior surgery. (c) Axial CTA image shows a CPB site pseudoaneurysm (arrow) in the ascending aorta located adjacent to a clip that had been placed for closure."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig28a.jpeg" height="1175" width="1257" aria-labelledby="fig28a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28a</span>. Pledget mimicking a pseudoaneurysm and a CPB cannulation site pseudoaneurysm. <b>(a)</b> Postcontrast axial CTA image shows an apparent outpouching (arrow) that can be interpreted as arising from the ascending aorta and potentially a small pseudoaneurysm. <b>(b)</b> Precontrast axial CT image shows the finding with high attenuation, consistent with a pledget (arrow). Note the sternotomy indicating prior surgery. <b>(c)</b> Axial CTA image shows a CPB site pseudoaneurysm (arrow) in the ascending aorta located adjacent to a clip that had been placed for closure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig28a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28b" class="graphic" aria-label="Pledget mimicking a pseudoaneurysm and a CPB cannulation site pseudoaneurysm. (a) Postcontrast axial CTA image shows an apparent outpouching (arrow) that can be interpreted as arising from the ascending aorta and potentially a small pseudoaneurysm. (b) Precontrast axial CT image shows the finding with high attenuation, consistent with a pledget (arrow). Note the sternotomy indicating prior surgery. (c) Axial CTA image shows a CPB site pseudoaneurysm (arrow) in the ascending aorta located adjacent to a clip that had been placed for closure."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig28b.jpeg" height="1175" width="1273" aria-labelledby="fig28b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28b</span>. Pledget mimicking a pseudoaneurysm and a CPB cannulation site pseudoaneurysm. <b>(a)</b> Postcontrast axial CTA image shows an apparent outpouching (arrow) that can be interpreted as arising from the ascending aorta and potentially a small pseudoaneurysm. <b>(b)</b> Precontrast axial CT image shows the finding with high attenuation, consistent with a pledget (arrow). Note the sternotomy indicating prior surgery. <b>(c)</b> Axial CTA image shows a CPB site pseudoaneurysm (arrow) in the ascending aorta located adjacent to a clip that had been placed for closure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig28b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28c" class="graphic" aria-label="Pledget mimicking a pseudoaneurysm and a CPB cannulation site pseudoaneurysm. (a) Postcontrast axial CTA image shows an apparent outpouching (arrow) that can be interpreted as arising from the ascending aorta and potentially a small pseudoaneurysm. (b) Precontrast axial CT image shows the finding with high attenuation, consistent with a pledget (arrow). Note the sternotomy indicating prior surgery. (c) Axial CTA image shows a CPB site pseudoaneurysm (arrow) in the ascending aorta located adjacent to a clip that had been placed for closure."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig28c.jpeg" height="1175" width="1169" aria-labelledby="fig28c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28c</span>. Pledget mimicking a pseudoaneurysm and a CPB cannulation site pseudoaneurysm. <b>(a)</b> Postcontrast axial CTA image shows an apparent outpouching (arrow) that can be interpreted as arising from the ascending aorta and potentially a small pseudoaneurysm. <b>(b)</b> Precontrast axial CT image shows the finding with high attenuation, consistent with a pledget (arrow). Note the sternotomy indicating prior surgery. <b>(c)</b> Axial CTA image shows a CPB site pseudoaneurysm (arrow) in the ascending aorta located adjacent to a clip that had been placed for closure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig28c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29a" class="graphic" aria-label="Aortic interposition graft. (a, b) Axial nonehanced image (a) shows high attenuation in the ascending aorta wall (arrow), which can mimic an IMH, which on the axial postcontrast CT image (b) is not appreciable. (c) Coronal CTA image shows narrowing, creating “waists” (arrows) at the anastomotic regions of the graft with the aorta."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig29a.jpeg" height="1198" width="1208" aria-labelledby="fig29a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29a</span>. Aortic interposition graft. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial nonehanced image <b>(a)</b> shows high attenuation in the ascending aorta wall (arrow), which can mimic an IMH, which on the axial postcontrast CT image <b>(b)</b> is not appreciable. <b>(c)</b> Coronal CTA image shows narrowing, creating “waists” (arrows) at the anastomotic regions of the graft with the aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig29a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29b" class="graphic" aria-label="Aortic interposition graft. (a, b) Axial nonehanced image (a) shows high attenuation in the ascending aorta wall (arrow), which can mimic an IMH, which on the axial postcontrast CT image (b) is not appreciable. (c) Coronal CTA image shows narrowing, creating “waists” (arrows) at the anastomotic regions of the graft with the aorta."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig29b.jpeg" height="1198" width="1310" aria-labelledby="fig29b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29b</span>. Aortic interposition graft. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial nonehanced image <b>(a)</b> shows high attenuation in the ascending aorta wall (arrow), which can mimic an IMH, which on the axial postcontrast CT image <b>(b)</b> is not appreciable. <b>(c)</b> Coronal CTA image shows narrowing, creating “waists” (arrows) at the anastomotic regions of the graft with the aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig29b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29c" class="graphic" aria-label="Aortic interposition graft. (a, b) Axial nonehanced image (a) shows high attenuation in the ascending aorta wall (arrow), which can mimic an IMH, which on the axial postcontrast CT image (b) is not appreciable. (c) Coronal CTA image shows narrowing, creating “waists” (arrows) at the anastomotic regions of the graft with the aorta."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig29c.jpeg" height="1198" width="1181" aria-labelledby="fig29c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29c</span>. Aortic interposition graft. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial nonehanced image <b>(a)</b> shows high attenuation in the ascending aorta wall (arrow), which can mimic an IMH, which on the axial postcontrast CT image <b>(b)</b> is not appreciable. <b>(c)</b> Coronal CTA image shows narrowing, creating “waists” (arrows) at the anastomotic regions of the graft with the aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig29c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30a" class="graphic" aria-label="Inclusion graft. (a) Axial nonenhanced CT image shows a linear area of high attenuation (arrow) mimicking dissection. (b) Axial CTA image shows that the linear area of high attenuation is the interface created by the anteriorly positioned graft lumen and posteriorly located perigraft space (arrow), which has both contrast enhancement consistent with a leak and mild soft-tissue attenuation related to partial thrombosis. (c) Coronal image shows the clip and waists (arrows), indicating graft location, adjacent to the thrombosed part of the perigraft space."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig30a.jpeg" height="1233" width="1140" aria-labelledby="fig30a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30a</span>. Inclusion graft. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows a linear area of high attenuation (arrow) mimicking dissection. <b>(b)</b> Axial CTA image shows that the linear area of high attenuation is the interface created by the anteriorly positioned graft lumen and posteriorly located perigraft space (arrow), which has both contrast enhancement consistent with a leak and mild soft-tissue attenuation related to partial thrombosis. <b>(c)</b> Coronal image shows the clip and waists (arrows), indicating graft location, adjacent to the thrombosed part of the perigraft space.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig30a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30b" class="graphic" aria-label="Inclusion graft. (a) Axial nonenhanced CT image shows a linear area of high attenuation (arrow) mimicking dissection. (b) Axial CTA image shows that the linear area of high attenuation is the interface created by the anteriorly positioned graft lumen and posteriorly located perigraft space (arrow), which has both contrast enhancement consistent with a leak and mild soft-tissue attenuation related to partial thrombosis. (c) Coronal image shows the clip and waists (arrows), indicating graft location, adjacent to the thrombosed part of the perigraft space."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig30b.jpeg" height="1233" width="1223" aria-labelledby="fig30b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30b</span>. Inclusion graft. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows a linear area of high attenuation (arrow) mimicking dissection. <b>(b)</b> Axial CTA image shows that the linear area of high attenuation is the interface created by the anteriorly positioned graft lumen and posteriorly located perigraft space (arrow), which has both contrast enhancement consistent with a leak and mild soft-tissue attenuation related to partial thrombosis. <b>(c)</b> Coronal image shows the clip and waists (arrows), indicating graft location, adjacent to the thrombosed part of the perigraft space.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig30b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30c" class="graphic" aria-label="Inclusion graft. (a) Axial nonenhanced CT image shows a linear area of high attenuation (arrow) mimicking dissection. (b) Axial CTA image shows that the linear area of high attenuation is the interface created by the anteriorly positioned graft lumen and posteriorly located perigraft space (arrow), which has both contrast enhancement consistent with a leak and mild soft-tissue attenuation related to partial thrombosis. (c) Coronal image shows the clip and waists (arrows), indicating graft location, adjacent to the thrombosed part of the perigraft space."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig30c.jpeg" height="1233" width="1336" aria-labelledby="fig30c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30c</span>. Inclusion graft. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows a linear area of high attenuation (arrow) mimicking dissection. <b>(b)</b> Axial CTA image shows that the linear area of high attenuation is the interface created by the anteriorly positioned graft lumen and posteriorly located perigraft space (arrow), which has both contrast enhancement consistent with a leak and mild soft-tissue attenuation related to partial thrombosis. <b>(c)</b> Coronal image shows the clip and waists (arrows), indicating graft location, adjacent to the thrombosed part of the perigraft space.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig30c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31a" class="graphic" aria-label="Elephant trunk procedure for type A dissection with aneurysm formation. (a) Axial nonenhanced CT image obtained after stage 1 repair shows two graft flaps (arrows) that can mimic dissection. (b) Axial CTA image shows aortic debranching, with common graft of reimplanted arch branch vessels (arrow) arising from the ascending aortic graft (arrowhead). (c) Off-sagittal oblique CTA reformation shows a graft in the ascending aorta (arrows), with the free ends in the proximal descending aorta (arrowheads). (d) Off-sagittal oblique image obtained after stage 2 repair shows a new endovascular stent in the distal arch and descending aorta."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig31a.jpeg" height="1241" width="1317" aria-labelledby="fig31a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31a</span>. Elephant trunk procedure for type A dissection with aneurysm formation. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image obtained after stage 1 repair shows two graft flaps (arrows) that can mimic dissection. <b>(b)</b> Axial CTA image shows aortic debranching, with common graft of reimplanted arch branch vessels (arrow) arising from the ascending aortic graft (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Off-sagittal oblique CTA reformation shows a graft in the ascending aorta (arrows), with the free ends in the proximal descending aorta (arrowheads). <b>(d)</b> Off-sagittal oblique image obtained after stage 2 repair shows a new endovascular stent in the distal arch and descending aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig31a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31b" class="graphic" aria-label="Elephant trunk procedure for type A dissection with aneurysm formation. (a) Axial nonenhanced CT image obtained after stage 1 repair shows two graft flaps (arrows) that can mimic dissection. (b) Axial CTA image shows aortic debranching, with common graft of reimplanted arch branch vessels (arrow) arising from the ascending aortic graft (arrowhead). (c) Off-sagittal oblique CTA reformation shows a graft in the ascending aorta (arrows), with the free ends in the proximal descending aorta (arrowheads). (d) Off-sagittal oblique image obtained after stage 2 repair shows a new endovascular stent in the distal arch and descending aorta."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig31b.jpeg" height="1241" width="1334" aria-labelledby="fig31b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31b</span>. Elephant trunk procedure for type A dissection with aneurysm formation. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image obtained after stage 1 repair shows two graft flaps (arrows) that can mimic dissection. <b>(b)</b> Axial CTA image shows aortic debranching, with common graft of reimplanted arch branch vessels (arrow) arising from the ascending aortic graft (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Off-sagittal oblique CTA reformation shows a graft in the ascending aorta (arrows), with the free ends in the proximal descending aorta (arrowheads). <b>(d)</b> Off-sagittal oblique image obtained after stage 2 repair shows a new endovascular stent in the distal arch and descending aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig31b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31c" class="graphic" aria-label="Elephant trunk procedure for type A dissection with aneurysm formation. (a) Axial nonenhanced CT image obtained after stage 1 repair shows two graft flaps (arrows) that can mimic dissection. (b) Axial CTA image shows aortic debranching, with common graft of reimplanted arch branch vessels (arrow) arising from the ascending aortic graft (arrowhead). (c) Off-sagittal oblique CTA reformation shows a graft in the ascending aorta (arrows), with the free ends in the proximal descending aorta (arrowheads). (d) Off-sagittal oblique image obtained after stage 2 repair shows a new endovascular stent in the distal arch and descending aorta."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig31c.jpeg" height="1490" width="1320" aria-labelledby="fig31c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31c</span>. Elephant trunk procedure for type A dissection with aneurysm formation. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image obtained after stage 1 repair shows two graft flaps (arrows) that can mimic dissection. <b>(b)</b> Axial CTA image shows aortic debranching, with common graft of reimplanted arch branch vessels (arrow) arising from the ascending aortic graft (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Off-sagittal oblique CTA reformation shows a graft in the ascending aorta (arrows), with the free ends in the proximal descending aorta (arrowheads). <b>(d)</b> Off-sagittal oblique image obtained after stage 2 repair shows a new endovascular stent in the distal arch and descending aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig31c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31d" class="graphic" aria-label="Elephant trunk procedure for type A dissection with aneurysm formation. (a) Axial nonenhanced CT image obtained after stage 1 repair shows two graft flaps (arrows) that can mimic dissection. (b) Axial CTA image shows aortic debranching, with common graft of reimplanted arch branch vessels (arrow) arising from the ascending aortic graft (arrowhead). (c) Off-sagittal oblique CTA reformation shows a graft in the ascending aorta (arrows), with the free ends in the proximal descending aorta (arrowheads). (d) Off-sagittal oblique image obtained after stage 2 repair shows a new endovascular stent in the distal arch and descending aorta."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig31d.jpeg" height="1490" width="1331" aria-labelledby="fig31d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31d</span>. Elephant trunk procedure for type A dissection with aneurysm formation. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image obtained after stage 1 repair shows two graft flaps (arrows) that can mimic dissection. <b>(b)</b> Axial CTA image shows aortic debranching, with common graft of reimplanted arch branch vessels (arrow) arising from the ascending aortic graft (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Off-sagittal oblique CTA reformation shows a graft in the ascending aorta (arrows), with the free ends in the proximal descending aorta (arrowheads). <b>(d)</b> Off-sagittal oblique image obtained after stage 2 repair shows a new endovascular stent in the distal arch and descending aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig31d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig32a" class="graphic" aria-label="Oversewn side-arm grafts for CPB. (a) Coronal MPR CTA image in a patient who underwent arch repair shows contrast material outpouching (arrow), representing a sewn-over side-arm graft used for CPB rather than a pseudoaneurysm. Note the clips located superior to the finding. (b) Coronal MPR CT image in a different patient after stage 1 repair of an elephant trunk procedure shows a small outpouching of contrast material arising from the distal aortic graft (white arrow), reflecting an oversewn side-arm graft. Note the adjacent suture line (red arrow) used for closure."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig32a.jpeg" height="1259" width="2110" aria-labelledby="fig32a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 32a</span>. Oversewn side-arm grafts for CPB. <b>(a)</b> Coronal MPR CTA image in a patient who underwent arch repair shows contrast material outpouching (arrow), representing a sewn-over side-arm graft used for CPB rather than a pseudoaneurysm. Note the clips located superior to the finding. <b>(b)</b> Coronal MPR CT image in a different patient after stage 1 repair of an elephant trunk procedure shows a small outpouching of contrast material arising from the distal aortic graft (white arrow), reflecting an oversewn side-arm graft. Note the adjacent suture line (red arrow) used for closure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig32a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig32b" class="graphic" aria-label="Oversewn side-arm grafts for CPB. (a) Coronal MPR CTA image in a patient who underwent arch repair shows contrast material outpouching (arrow), representing a sewn-over side-arm graft used for CPB rather than a pseudoaneurysm. Note the clips located superior to the finding. (b) Coronal MPR CT image in a different patient after stage 1 repair of an elephant trunk procedure shows a small outpouching of contrast material arising from the distal aortic graft (white arrow), reflecting an oversewn side-arm graft. Note the adjacent suture line (red arrow) used for closure."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200055/asset/images/large/rg.2021200055.fig32b.jpeg" height="1259" width="1041" aria-labelledby="fig32b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 32b</span>. Oversewn side-arm grafts for CPB. <b>(a)</b> Coronal MPR CTA image in a patient who underwent arch repair shows contrast material outpouching (arrow), representing a sewn-over side-arm graft used for CPB rather than a pseudoaneurysm. Note the clips located superior to the finding. <b>(b)</b> Coronal MPR CT image in a different patient after stage 1 repair of an elephant trunk procedure shows a small outpouching of contrast material arising from the distal aortic graft (white arrow), reflecting an oversewn side-arm graft. Note the adjacent suture line (red arrow) used for closure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200055&amp;id=fig32b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Mussa FF, Horton JD, Moridzadeh R, Nicholson J, Trimarchi S, Eagle KA. Acute Aortic Dissection and Intramural Hematoma: A Systematic Review. <em>JAMA</em> 2016;316(7):754–763.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1001/jama.2016.10026">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27533160/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Acute+Aortic+Dissection+and+Intramural+Hematoma%3A+A+Systematic+Review&amp;author=FF+Mussa&amp;author=JD+Horton&amp;author=R+Moridzadeh&amp;author=J+Nicholson&amp;author=S+Trimarchi&amp;author=KA+Eagle&amp;publication_year=2016&amp;journal=JAMA&amp;pages=754-763&amp;doi=10.1001%2Fjama.2016.10026&amp;pmid=27533160">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Wee I, Varughese RS, Syn N, Choong AMTL. Non-operative Management of Type A Acute Aortic Syndromes: A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis. <em>Eur J Vasc Endovasc Surg</e